INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (594, 1, '2012-08-28 19:05:53', '2012-08-28 19:05:53', '<h1>Right now</h1>\r\nI am a Web Designer and Front-end Developer who currently works for the web team at the <a href="http://www.leeds.ac.uk">University of Leeds</a>. I split my time between my day job, freelance work, running <a href="http://www.manchestersfinest.com">manchestersfinest.com</a> and <a href="http://soundcloud.com/matt_tyas">making music</a>. From time to time I also write my <a href="/out-of-my-head/">blog</a>.\r\n<h1>But it wasn\'t always soâ€¦</h1>\r\n<h2><em>â€œThis is the eighties, anything is possibleâ€¦â€</em></h2>\r\nBack in the eighties, my HTML was cardboard and my CSS, Sellotape. I just loved making things. Inventions and contraptions to solve my every problems. Problems such as:\r\n<blockquote>â€œHow do I get a Malteser in my mouth without having to get out of bed or move any of my limbs?â€</blockquote>\r\nThis was how the, \'Tonka Truck Malteser Race Track Delivery Device â„¢\', or, \'TTMRTDD\', was born. I am currently in a legal battle with Apple over this one.\r\n<h2>The world\'s worst website</h2>\r\nWhen I was 13 I built a website. We had dial up Compuserve internet. It was called, "Matthew Tyas\'s website" (because I couldn\'t change the page title) and it consisted of a home page, and a contact page with nothing but a clip art email link that didn\'t work. In fact, none of the links worked. I managed, however, to upload one MS Paint image. It was a scrawl that said,\r\n<blockquote>â€œWelcome to the world\'s worst websiteâ€</blockquote>\r\n<h2>Do you want to employ me yet? Wait, I\'ve not finished!</h2>\r\nI forgot about the web for a while and concentrated on graphic design (back then I didn\'t really associate much of what I saw on the internet with design anywayâ€¦) but later at <a href="http://www2.mmu.ac.uk/" target="_blank">Manchester Metropolitan University</a>, whilst studying <a href="http://www.designandartdirection.mmu.ac.uk/" target="_blank">Design &amp; Art Direction</a> I started to notice interactions, and user experience on web sites. At this point I started to realise that designing for the web was a type of design in itself. Design that needed to flex, grow and accomodate multiple situations and multiple use cases.\r\n\r\nFrom then on it was a dash to learn everything I could about web design, coding and UX.\r\n<h2>Today, this type of design still excites me the most.</h2>\r\nEvery time I approach a new project there are new techniques to implement. New approaches to RWD\r\n\r\nPlanning, researching, problem solving, designing, building, testing, re-testing, re-designing, re-building, testing again, until you have\r\n\r\nSorry, I am still writing this thrilling storyâ€¦', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '16-revision-27', '', '', '2012-08-28 19:05:53', '2012-08-28 19:05:53', '', 16, 'http://matthewtyas.com/16-revision-27/', 0, 'revision', '', 0); 
